  "prompt": "How can you see if someone deleted you on LINE?",
  "response": "Unfortunately, LINE doesn't provide a direct notification when someone removes you from their friends list. However, you can use a few methods to infer whether or not someone has removed you. These methods aren't foolproof, but they can give you a good indication:\n\n**1. Check for Profile Updates:**\n\n*   **No Recent Updates:** If you used to see frequent profile updates (profile picture, status message) from the person, and they've suddenly stopped, it could mean they've removed you. When someone removes you, you can no longer see their profile updates.\n*   **Check if it's been a while since you last spoke:** If it's been months since you've talked, they might be less likely to remove you.\n\n**Important Note:** This method isn't conclusive. They may simply not be active on LINE anymore, or they may have changed their privacy settings.\n\n**2. Send a Message (and Observe):**\n\n*   **Single Checkmark (Not Read):** If you send a message and it only shows a single checkmark for a long time (days or weeks), it could indicate you've been removed. The single checkmark means the message has been sent from your device but hasn't been delivered to the recipient's device.  Keep in mind they could be offline, have notifications turned off, or have poor internet connection.\n*   **If they still appear in your chat list:** It could also mean they have blocked you.\n\n**Important Note:** This isn't 100% accurate. The recipient might simply be inactive, have a weak internet connection, or have blocked you. If a message hasn't been read after a very long time (several weeks), it's more likely they've removed or blocked you.\n\n**3. Try to Send a Gift:**\n\n*   **Cannot Send Gift:** Try to send a sticker or theme as a gift to the person. If you receive an error message that says you cannot send a gift to that person, it is a strong indication that they have either blocked you or removed you from their friends list. LINE often treats these two actions similarly when it comes to gifting.\n\n**Important Note:** This is one of the most reliable indicators. However, sometimes there are temporary technical issues with sending gifts, so try again later if you're unsure. Also, if the person is using a device with a different OS than your device, you might also have trouble sending gift.\n\n**4. Check Shared Groups:**\n\n*   **If you share a group with the person:** If you have a shared LINE group with the person, you can check their profile within the group.  If you can see their profile there, then they haven't blocked you. This doesn't necessarily mean they haven't unfriended you, but it rules out the \"blocked\" scenario.\n\n**5. Create a Group (Most Definitive, but noticeable):**\n\n*   **Attempt to add them to a new group:** This is the most direct way to find out, but it also alerts the person that you're trying to contact them. Try to create a new group and add the person to it.\n    *   **If you can't add them:**  It is most likely that you were either blocked or unfriended.\n    *   **If you can add them:**  Then, they have not unfriended you.\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **Blocking vs. Removing:** LINE doesn't explicitly differentiate between being blocked and being removed in many of these situations. Many of the above symptoms can indicate either action.\n*   **Privacy Settings:** The user may have adjusted their privacy settings to limit who can see their profile updates or send them messages.\n*   **Activity:** The user may simply be inactive on LINE.\n\n**In summary, there's no definitive way to know for sure if someone has removed you from LINE without directly asking them (which you might not want to do). Use a combination of the methods above to form an educated guess. The \"sending a gift\" method is generally the most reliable.**\n",
